    "summary": "The Sino-Soviet Split was the deterioration of relations between the People's Republic of China and the Soviet Union that escalated through the late 1950s and reached open rupture by the mid-1960s. Despite sharing communist ideology, the two nations' ideological differences, national interests, and leadership rivalries drove them apart. Mao Zedong criticized Soviet leader Nikita Khrushchev's policy of peaceful coexistence with the West and his denunciation of Stalin's crimes as ideological revisionism and capitulation.\n\nThe split had immediate practical consequences. The Soviet Union withdrew thousands of technical advisers from China in 1960, halting numerous infrastructure and industrial projects. Chinese and Soviet communist parties openly condemned each other in publications and international forums. Border disputes — dormant under communist solidarity — re-emerged with dangerous intensity, culminating in armed clashes along the Ussuri River in 1969 that brought the two nuclear powers to the brink of war.\n\nThe Sino-Soviet Split fundamentally restructured Cold War geopolitics. China emerged as a potential counterweight to Soviet power, which [[event:3649|Nixon exploited when he visited China]] in 1972. The split also complicated revolutionary movements globally, forcing leftist parties and movements to choose between Chinese and Soviet lines. The rupture demonstrated that communist solidarity could not indefinitely override the competing national interests of major states, and it permanently altered the strategic landscape of the second half of the twentieth century.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sino-Soviet_split",
